May 17th, 1940 - On this day in World War Two history, Germans take Brussels, Belgium.
Belgium itself would not surrender until May 28th, around the same time that the allied troops were evacuating Dunkirk in Northern France.
The Belgians knew that without the allied armies of France and Great Britain, it would be futile to try and resist the German Army. Their hopes were pinned on the success of the allies, and when that faded into a lost hope, they submitted to Germany. 
France sooner fell as well, and by July, the U.K. was hanging on by a thread due to German Luftwaffe bombings. 
The Belgians had survived without their capital for 11 days, and lost thousand of men, women, and children in pointless resistance. The fall of Belgium was surprising, but not unexpected. The Fall of France though, on June 22nd of 1940, was a complete shock, and it truly woke up the world (namely America) into an understanding that this war was truly going to be a global cause.
Belgium was meant to The the true battleground of WW2, where the allies believed their armies would clash with the proven German war machine, and that it might again turn into a horrible trench war just like the First World War. 
The Germans actually had initially planned to carry out the exact same plan as they had done in WW1, except this time, with Blitzkrieg. That was until Erich von Manstein proposed the plan that would be used. This, as I have said many times, involved Panzer units moving through the Ardennes in secrecy as a decoy army moved through The Netherlands, Luxembourg, and Belgium so the allies would be drawn further east. This Ardennes Army Group (Army Group A) would then exit the western side of the Ardennes and move swiftly upwards, cutting off and encircling the French and British armies and forcing them to evacuate. Belgium was only fought in for a couple of weeks due to the speed and ferocity of the German advance. This picture depicts Belgian troops before the capitulation of their country on a Vickers Utility Tractor.

Johannes Steinhoff (1913- 1994)

This famous and former Luftwaffe ace who fought on the Eastern Front, Western Front and in the Mediterranean had a record of 176 destroyed aircrafts and was shot down 12 times during the war, only bailing out once,  Steinhoff said" i only bailed out once, i never trusted the parachutes so i always landed my damaged planes hoping not to get bounced on the way down when i lost power". Awarded with high decorations as the Knights Cross with Oak Leaves and Swords his World War participation would en in April 1945 when trying to take off with the jet fighter Messerschmitt Me 262.
His plane suffered a tyre blow and crashed, the plane catched fire and Steinhoff suffered severe burns which led to two years in hospital and left him scarred for life, swipe to see the scars!

During the Cold War he was invited by the government in West Germany to rebuild the Luftwaffe within NATO which he did and rised to general.

After his retirement from NATO he wrote a couple of books on the German military aviation such as "Messerschmitts over Sicily" and The Final Hours". Steinhoff passed away from a heart attack in 1995.

May 14th, 1940 - On this day in World War Two history, The Netherlands surrenders to Germany after the bombing of Rotterdam. Also, Britain forms Local Defence Volunteers (later called the Home Guard); more than 250,000 men aged 17-65 enroll in the first 24 hours.
With the Netherlands surrendering to Germany, the only free countries in the west that remained were Belgium, France, and the U.K. 
With the effective German invasion plan of France, which involved German Panzer divisions surprising the French and British armies after secretly moving through the Ardennes, the allied armies were forced out of Belgium in an attempt to flee encirclement, but this was futile. On May 28th, Belgium would surrender, and on June 22nd, France itself would fall.
At the end of May and the beginning of June, the allies evacuated at the French port of Dunkirk to England. Of the 400,000 allied troops of the French and British armies, around 340,000 escaped to England, and most of the troops that were left behind were French. A little while later, the French had their own mini evacuation, but this was very small in comparison to Dunkirk.
With the majority of the allied troops out of France, the rest of the country was pretty much destined to fall. 
The fall of France hit the world hard, especially in America and Great Britain.
The Americans had been a nation majorly neutral with feeling of not getting dragged into another European conflict. The fall of France though, made a lot of Americans realize that this war might reach them whether they liked it or not, as Great Britain stood as the only beacon of Democracy left in Europe.
The majority was still towards neutrality after the fall of France, but the percentages changed so that more were ok with American intervention. It would not be until the Japanese attack on Pearl Harbor that the majority would move for war, but you cannot say that was the only event that changed how Americans felt about the conflict.
